metadata.name: (Anti)thesis #94
metadata.description:
This is my first fxhash work. It is a generative, deterministic, object-oriented algorithm written entirely in p5.js. With the exception of two very rare background colours, the colour palettes are not pre-selected but entirely generated using your transaction hash.

The algorithm plays on the concept of Antithesis (/ænˈtɪθəsɪs/ - direct contrast; opposition) by using opposing forces to generate tension (and occasional calm) between forms on the page and the spaces in between. Inspiration was also drawn from works and advice from the great Daniel Catt (@revdancatt).

I hope you like it. Thanks for your support.
tallzy

metadata.name: Hotlines #239
metadata.description:
Hotlines by CMPLX | 2022

Mint 10 or more to receive a free physical print.

What’s in a line? 

Is a line simply a connection between point A and point B, or does it tell a story?

Explore the possibilities of minimalist composition building through line, shape, color, and texture. These elements combine to form a minimalist’s playground. What can you create? 

Compositions are created primarily through random paths superimposed upon additional visual elements and range from extremely minimalist to more chaotic depending on the hash. 

Hotlines compositions are unique and randomly produced based on your mint. 

Consisting of several composition elements including grid, color, lineweight, texture, etc. The project is designed and priced to encourage multiple mints per individual to allow for more playful arrangements to build your collection. 

Landscape / Portrait / Square are all possible per mint.

1080x720 / 720x1080 / 1080x1080

“s” to save as .png 

DM @c_mplx for physical print verification and address.

metadata.name: View #41
metadata.description:
Generative art is rarely representational, this work seeks to explore what can be achieved by an algorithm with the medium of pixel art. 

The algorithm generates a 200x200 pixel art image showing a view from a window over the sea. There are three backdrops available, all completely procedural. No baked-in sprites were used. I hope that the love that went into making it is clear.


Please enjoy the view.

metadata.name: Esagoni #82
metadata.description:
A piece stepping away from control and leaning into minimalism, there are several factors at play to make your Esagoni unique. Both of the two hexagon colors are a random RGB value, at various luminosities.

The root of separation chooses which color takes the lead, between 1-100, 50 being evenly distributed.

The separation between the two colors can vary from 0-100, 0 is a 1% chance.

Modifiers can be either Circular or Hexagonal.

The scale of the hexagons on the grid varies from 1-100.

There is a 10% chance of a monochrome Esagoni, 5% respectively to both "Black on White" and "White on Black."


This piece can also be changed to infinite resolutions, for any frame or screen you'd like to display it on.

In live view, press:

'w' to view in 16:9

't' to view in 8x10

's' to view in 1x1

'f' to adapt to your own screen size

Double-click to save image

Enjoy :)

metadata.description:
Drag to rotate, scroll to zoom.

During the 1969 observation of a completely dark region of the sky a long repeating signal was recorded. 
Encoded within the sound wave were distinct 96 patterns resembling celestial bodies. A series of tablets from these patterns were crafted using precious earth metals.
To this day nobody deciphered the signal’s meaning, but the unique patterns became known as the Strands.

metadata.name: Seasons #201
metadata.description:
Seasons depicts monolithic mountains and calm seas scattered with unnatural elements.
The color palettes explore the colors of natural landscapes through different times of year.

To ease browser load, the images are paused by default.
Hitting 'p' will toggle a subtle animation.
Hitting 't' will toggle between the day and night palette for the image.
On mobile the resolution is reduced and the image is always paused to ease the load on the device.

Generative images by 0x3739
twitter.com/0x3739
library: twgljs - A Tiny WebGL helper Library
license: CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
Tested and functioning correctly on Google Chrome version 100.0.4896.88 on Windows desktop and Android mobile device.

The work is rendered in webgl as a fragment shader.
Setting parameters in the javascript portion of the script generates a different fragment shader for each iteration.

Interactions
'-' to zoom in.
'+' to zoom out.
'f' to change the aspect ratio to fullscreen.
'z' to change the aspect ratio to square.
'a' to change the aspect ratio to A4/A3/A2/A1 format.
'w' to change the aspect ratio to 16:9.
'q' to change the aspect ratio to portrait.
's' to save an image of the canvas.
'p' to pause the animation the image.
't' to toggle the time (day/night) in the image.
'b' to toggle the margins on the image.
'm' to toggle the mountains in the image.
'c' to toggle the clouds in the image.
'g' to toggle the grid in the image.
'd' to toggle the dirt speckles in the image.
'n' to toggle the noise in the image.
'j' to toggle the jitter in the image.
'v' to toggle all vintage effects in the image.
'1' to toggle the stars in the image.
'2' to toggle the moons in the image.
'3' to toggle the black squares in the image.
'4' to toggle the white squares in the image.
'5' to toggle the primary color squares in the image.
'6' to toggle the secundary color squares in the image.
'7' to toggle the colour correction in the image.
'8' to toggle the sea in the image.
'h' to increase the quality modifier (maximum is 3).
'l' to decrease the quality modifier (minimum is 1).
The quality modifier is a modifier on the width and height of the canvas.
Changing the modifier can affect the look of the image due to subpixel artifacts.
The modifier can be used to save higher resolution images.
Higher values of the modifier increase memory usage and can cause a browser or webgl instance to crash. 
'arrow_up' to move up in the image.
'arrow_down' to move down in the image.
'arrow_right' to move right in the image.
'arrow_left' to move left in the image.
